### 2. 📥 `git clone` — Getting Code from GitHub

The practical focus shifted to **how to work across multiple machines** — the real-world scenario of committing at school and continuing at home (or vice versa).

- **`git clone <url>`** — downloads a full copy of a GitHub repository including all history
- After cloning, Git already knows the remote connection — `git push` works without re-specifying the origin
- The cloned repo is in exactly the same state as it was when last pushed — you pick up right where you left off
- Students were reminded to **always run `git status` first** when sitting down at a new machine, before making any changes

---

### 3. 📋 `git log` — Reading Commit History

The instructor demonstrated `git log` as a way to inspect the history of a repo:

- Shows each commit with its **hash**, **author**, **timestamp**, and **message**
- The **commit hash** is a long unique string of letters and numbers — a fingerprint for that exact snapshot
- You only need the **first 6–7 characters** of a hash to reference a specific commit in Git commands
- `git log --oneline` was shown as a compact view — one commit per line
- `git log --all` shows commits from all branches, not just the current one

